Definitively confirmed. Here's the real diagnosis:

The pattern didn't degrade — it was never able to run. The venv is correctly configured for the target dir. The crash is: there is no python on PATH in the image.

_docker/image/Dockerfile sets POETRY_VIRTUALENVS_PATH=/workspace/target/python-venvs/ (correct — that's the overlaid target volume, so a forked sandbox's poetry install copies-up into its own overlay and never pollutes the frozen /workspace base).
Dockerfile.base sets PATH=/usr/local/python/bin:$PATH + UV_PYTHON_INSTALL_DIR=/usr/local/python intending a uv-managed interpreter there — but there is no uv python install step, so /usr/local/python never exists. The image ships only python3/python3.13, no bare python.
Poetry 2.4.1 and virtualenv shell out to a bare python → FileNotFoundError: 'python' → poetry install dies → _cont_start.sh (set -e) exits → restart: unless-stopped → crash loop.
The in-project .venv you saw was a red herring from my messy manual test sequence, not the real behavior. Proven above: with a python present, both the reuse case and a fresh create land in POETRY_VIRTUALENVS_PATH, never in-project. The one-line fix belongs in the image so sandboxes inherit it too:

